##Italy's worst-hit region, with schools suspended and supermarkets snapped up

Many people wear face masks in front of the Cathedral Square in downtown Milan, Italy, on Feb. 23. FIGURE / method new

By Jiang Wei, CAIJING reporter

Editor | Hao Zhou

With the closure of the city, the cancellation of the Serie A match, the suspension of university classes, the suspension of the opera and the closure of the church, Italy was plunged into a state of emergency with a dramatic outbreak of COVID-19 pneumonia. As of the afternoon of February 23 local time, a total of 152 confirmed cases had been identified in Italy, of which three died within 48 hours. Three days ago, there were only three confirmed cases in Italy.

"I am surprised by the outbreak of these cases, " Prime Minister Contes told Italian media, adding that more cases are likely in Italy in the coming days. Because of the rapid rise in confirmed cases, Italy has become the most affected country outside of Asia. To control the spread of the virus, the Italian government from February 22 in 11 towns in the "closed" initiative. In the closed area, access is restricted to those with special passes.

"The window of opportunity is narrowing and we must seize the moment to prevent a wider global crisis, " WHO spokesman Tariq Jasarevic told Caijing

The outbreak has taken a turn for the worse

Italy on January 30, a husband and wife tourists from Wuhan infected with the new coronavirus, the country's first confirmed case. Then Italy suspended all flights to and from China and imposed a six-month state of emergency. There was no significant increase in the number of confirmed cases in Italy for some time after that, until the situation suddenly took a turn for the worse in the last two days. The confirmed Italian cases so far have mainly come from the northern regions of Lombardy and Veneto. Two of the worst hit areas contribute 30% of the country's GDP to Italy's economic heartland.

Following an emergency cabinet meeting on February 22, Italian Prime Minister Contes announced a series of emergency measures that night, including the closure of 11 municipalities in the Lombardy and Veneto regions. Access to the blocked area is currently controlled by the police, all public activities are suspended and traffic is restricted, affecting about 50,000 people. Violators of the quarantine requirements will be punished with up to three months in prison or a fine of up to 206 euros.

Three Serie A games scheduled for Tuesday night have been postponed due to the rapid spread of COVID-19 pneumonia in Italy, including a home game against Sampdoria. The Italian Ministry of Education has issued a notice requiring universities in the Lombardy, Veneto and Emilia-Romagna regions to suspend teaching until February 29.

Zhou Minxue is a Chinese student at the University of Turin in the city of Turin, which is part of the Piedmont region. Although not part of the three regions, there have been six confirmed cases. She received a notice from the school at 8 pm on the 23rd to suspend classes until the 29th. The resumption of classes is still pending further notice. "I was worried about my family, but now my family is worried about me, " Zhou min-xue, from Ezhou, told Caijing. Disinfectant, hand sanitizer and face masks are no longer available in the nearby pharmacies.

On the 23rd, Zhou min-xue went to the supermarket to buy food. She saw that the goods on the shelves were adequate. But another Chinese student living in Milan found that the shelves of the supermarket where he went were almost completely sold out. "It wasn't like this the day before, " he told Caijing.

Of the 152 confirmed cases so far, 110 are from Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. . Milan is the capital of the region, although confirmed cases are mainly concentrated in the southern towns of Milan, but out of concern for the spread of the virus, Milan Cathedral will be temporarily closed to visitors until February 25; The Teatro Alla Scala in Milan announced on the 23rd that it was suspending its theatrical performances; schools in Milan were closed for a week.

Milan fashion week was drawing to a close when the new coronavirus broke out in Italy. Luxury Label Armani Giorgio Armani said it was due to finish fashion show without an audience.

The number of confirmed cases is closely followed in Lombardy 见 Lombardia，Reg. By the Veneto region, whose capital is Venice. The Venice Carnival, which began on February 8th and runs until February 25th, was halted for the last three days by Veneto's chief executive, Lucca Zaia.

"The [ Italian ] health authorities have taken a series of measures to prevent further spread, such as closing schools, bars, stopping sporting events and other large gatherings. This is consistent with China's containment strategy,"Jasarovic told CAIJING.

Looking for Italian patient zero

Roberto Júlio de Figueiredo Speranza, Italy's health minister, said Italy was witnessing a cluster of cases similar to those in Germany and France. A spokesman for the World Health Organization, Giassarevic, also said the cluster of infections in northern Italy showed the first local spread in Italy. In his view, it was important to understand how things had evolved and to identify and track contacts.

But Angelo David Borrelli, head of Italy's Civil Protection Agency, said at a news conference on the 23rd: "We have not yet been able to identify who is patient zero, so it is difficult to predict new possible cases. "

Some of the new cases in Italy are from a hospital in Codogno, in the Lombardy region. A 38-year-old Italian man was the first confirmed case in the area. His wife and a friend were also tested positive after he was admitted to hospital with a new coronavirus. At the hospital where he was treated, three patients and five health care workers tested positive for the virus. His infected friend's father owns a bar and three elderly regulars have been diagnosed.

The Italian newspaper La Repubblica retraced the movements of patient number one. Before his diagnosis, he had traveled to the coastal city of Genoa on Feb. 2 to attend the half marathon, visited a bar with friends on Feb. 4, and ran another race on Feb. 9, meanwhile, I will continue to work at Unilever. On February 15, he attended a soccer match and a Red Cross training session and had dinner with two friends. He developed symptoms after the meal.

The man's route of infection is still unknown, so it is still not clear who is "patient zero. ". He dined with an Italian man who returned from China and developed flu symptoms in early February but tested negative for the virus.

"although the number of confirmed cases outside China is still relatively low, we are concerned about the lack of a clear epidemiological link, such as whether there has been any travel to China or exposure to confirmed cases, " said Jasarovitch.

Lucca Zaia, Veneto's regional chief executive, said the virus was spreading like a flu and that trying to pinpoint a single source or establish a link to China was no longer an effective containment measure. "You can get it from anyone. We will see confirmed patients who have no contact with suspected cases. "

The situation of some Chinese has been affected

The spread of the virus in Italy has also affected the situation of the local Chinese. At the end of January, a Music Academy in Rome, Italy, suspended classes for students from East Asian countries. A Chinese student studying in Turin told CAIJING that a teenager covered his mouth while avoiding him on the subway two weeks ago. But beyond that, there were no more unpleasant experiences. Images of vandalism or anti-china demonstrations against Chinese supermarkets on social media have also proved to be rumours.

But a Chinese woman became a victim of racism. On February 20th two Italians attacked a Chinese man who had lived in Turin for many years. According to the Italian "News" reported on the 23rd, the time of the incident in the daytime, the location of Turin City Center. "virus, get out of Turin, " the Chinese woman tried to explain, even though she was Chinese, when two Italians in their forty approached her at a traffic light and shouted obscenities at her, doesn't mean she has the virus. But the man continued to abuse her, and a woman with him attacked her. The mayor of Turin, Appendino, condemned the move as despicable.

For Chinese in Italy, the question is whether or not to wear a mask if one can buy one? In the eyes of locals, wearing a mask is only necessary in the event of illness, whereas the Chinese see wearing a mask as a way to protect themselves or others. With only one mask in her hand, Zhou min-xue decided to go out less. After witnessing the outbreak in her hometown, she was worried about Italians'lack of vigilance against the virus.
